        "date":  "2026-06-29",
        "theme":  "Philosophy",
        "summary":  "Research by Boston University professor Emma Wiles demonstrates that framing AI tools as digital employees reduces error detection by 18% and diminishes human accountability. The article warns against Silicon Valley\u0027s push to market AI agents as coworkers, arguing this approach undermines human oversight and creates unrealistic expectations.",
        "execSummary":  "This is one of the most decision-relevant pieces published this month for any leader deploying AI in customer-facing or operational roles: when employees are told AI is their \u0027coworker,\u0027 they catch 18% fewer AI errors and assign less personal accountability for outcomes. The finding directly challenges the anthropomorphic framing used by vendors like Microsoft (Copilot), Salesforce (Einstein), and others to drive adoption. For customer support leaders, the implication is that how you introduce AI to your team matters as much as what the AI can do ΓÇö framing it as a tool to be supervised will outperform framing it as a colleague to be trusted. This is an independent academic finding, not vendor-sponsored research.",
